article.description:
Before Chris Webber headed to the
playoffs and Juwan Howard headed to another early summer, the
longtime friends embraced after the final buzzer.
article.headline: Webber's underhand shot wins game
article.linkText: Webber saves Kings from defeat against Nuggets
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Before Chris Webber headed to the playoffs and Juwan Howard headed to another early summer, the longtime friends embraced after the final buzzer.
Chris Webber
Power Forward
Sacramento Kings
Profile
2002-2003 SEASON STATISTICS
GM PPG RPG APG FG% FT%
65 23.0 10.6 5.4 .460 .606
''You lucky son of a gun,'' Howard said with a grin. Webber scored 29 points and made an acrobatic underhand shot with 0.9 seconds left as the Sacramento Kings barely held off the Denver Nuggets for a 105-103 victory Friday night. It's more than luck that put the former Michigan collegiate stars on divergent paths since their four difficult seasons together in Washington. For starters, Webber is surrounded by teammates with enough talent to beat Howard's Nuggets for the eighth consecutive time despite one of Denver's best efforts in another nightmare season. The game was essentially meaningless for the Kings, who clinched their second consecutive Pacific Division title last week and will start the playoffs as the No. 2 seed in the West. Following the defeat Thursday night against the Los Angeles Lakers, they played with an obvious lack of emotion against the West's worst team. But Webber, who also had 10 rebounds and nine assists, shrugged off the Kings' frustrations for one spectacular winning shot. ''We play every game to win, but they're one of the elite teams, and we're the worst, record-wise,'' Denver's Marcus Camby said. ''In my opinion, Chris Webber is great. I don't care what other people think about him. He makes his team better.'' Howard scored 24 points for Denver, and his jumper with 1:12 left tied it at 101. After Webber and Peja Stojakovic each made one of two free throws, rookie Nene Hilario tied it again by tipping in Rodney White's shot with 22 seconds left. The Kings ran down the clock -- and Webber, again demonstrating his new determination to take Sacramento's biggest shots, split two defenders on the left wing and banked in an awkward long layup. ''You practice those little flip shots -- well, you don't really practice them, you just shoot them sometimes when you're goofing around,'' Webber said. ''For me, it's not just about taking the shot. It's just about having the ball in that situation.'' Shammond Williams missed a fallaway 3-pointer at the buzzer. The Kings played their second consecutive game of terrible defense, but still improved to an NBA-best 34-6 at home. Jim Jackson scored the Kings' first 11 points of the fourth quarter, while Stojakovic had 17 points and Vlade Divac 15. Hilario scored 18 points for the Nuggets, who stayed close throughout their fifth consecutive defeat. Camby had 11 points and 16 rebounds, while Williams scored all 15 of his points in the second half. The Kings followed an indifferent defensive performance against the Lakers with another stinker. Denver, the NBA's worst offensive team, lost its 13th in a row in Arco Arena despite leading for most of the first three quarters. Coach Rick Adelman wanted the victory to keep pressure on Dallas. Though the Kings (58-23) will be the No. 2 seed, they won't have home-court advantage in a possible second-round matchup with the Mavericks (57-22) unless Dallas struggles in its final four games. ''If we keep winning and Dallas loses another one, we have a good shot at catching them,'' Adelman said. ''We don't know who we're going to play in the playoffs. We just have to worry about ourselves.'' The Nuggets will miss the playoffs for the eighth consecutive season with their worst record since 1998 -- though you wouldn't know it from their gritty performance. Denver already has clinched last place in the Western Conference, though Cleveland probably will finish last in the league. ''The only thing we didn't do tonight is get a win,'' Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik said. ''We did so many things well that if we played teams other than Sacramento -- one or two other teams -- we would have had the win. Chris Webber is a great player, and great players can make and create shots to win games.'' After playing more games than the rest of the NBA for most of the regular season, the Kings get the next four days off before the season finale at home against Utah on Wednesday. Adelman gave his team the weekend off. Game notes
The Kings played without reserves Keon Clark (sinus infection) and Lawrence Funderburke (knee tendinitis). ... Devin Brown, the most valuable player and top rookie in the NBDL this season, made his first NBA start at shooting guard for the Nuggets, who signed the former Texas-San Antonio star last week. Brown, who played seven games for the Spurs earlier this season, scored eight points in 24 minutes. ... Donnell Harvey was scratched from the Nuggets' lineup after straining his lower back during pregame warmups.
